<subSubSection pageId="55" pageNumber="56" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="55.[151,1437,151,1151]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,982,1007]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Etymology.</emphasis>
From the Latin adjective, “ 
<emphasis box="[655,736,984,1007]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">griseus</emphasis>
”, meaning gray and the noun, “ 
<emphasis box="[1108,1164,983,1007]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">frons</emphasis>
”, meaning forehead, in reference to the grey tomentosity of the frons, a unique character in 
<taxonomicName box="[957,1055,1018,1043]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Houghia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[957,1055,1018,1043]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Houghia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
where the fronto-orbital plate is otherwise either silver or gold, not grey. The name is thus a noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
